<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:lang="en-US" xml:id="functions-graphical-transformations">
  <title>Graphical Transformations</title>

  <p>
    In this section we are going to explore the graphical repercussions of alterations to a given function formula.  Specifically, we are going to explore how the graph of the function <m>g</m> compares to the graph <m>f</m> where
    <me>g(x)=a \cdot f\left(b(x-h)\right)+k</me>
    for non-zero constants <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>h</m>, and <m>k</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    We will also consider the repercussions when
    <me>g(x)=a \cdot f(bx+c)+d</me>
    for nonzero constants <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>d</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before taking on the general cases, we need to examine the effects of minor, stand-alone, changes to the formula for <m>f</m>.
  </p>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Transformations of type <m>g(x)=f(x \pm h)</m></title>

    <p></p>
    <p>
      Before telling you the graphical effect of adding or subtracting a positive number to <m>x</m>, explore the effect yourself using <xref ref="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-1x">Figure</xref>.  Can you describe the effect using your own words?
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-1x">
      <caption>Add or subtract a positive number to <m>x</m> by dragging the slider.</caption>
      <interactive platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="9:5">
        <slate surface="geogebra" aspect="9:5" source="geogebra/function-horizontal-shifts.ggb">
              setPerspective("G");
              setAxisSteps(1, 1, 1, 1);
              setCoordSystem(-8, 8, -8, 8);
              setGridVisible(1);         
              setAxisLabels(1,"x","y","z");
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Assuming that <m>h</m> is a positive number, the graph of <m>y=f(x-h)</m> shifts every point on <m>y=f(x)</m> rightward by <m>h</m> units while the graph of <m>y=f(x+h)</m> shifts every point on <m>y=f(x)</m> leftward by <m>h</m> units.
    </p>
    <p>
      The graphs of <m>f(x)=\abs{x}</m> and <m>g(x)=\abs{x-3}</m> are shown in <xref ref="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-1">Figure</xref>.  Notice that <m>g</m> is the result of shifting <m>f</m> to the right by 3 units. The graphs of <m>f(x)=\abs{x}</m> and <m>h(x)=\abs{x+4}</m> are shown in <xref ref="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-2">Figure</xref>.  Notice that <m>h</m> is the result of shifting <m>f</m> to the left by 4 units.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

      <figure xml:id="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-1">
        <caption><m>\highlight{y=\abs{x}}\,\,\text{and}\,\,\highlightr{y=\abs{x-3}}</m></caption>
        <image>
          <description>
            A graph with several arrows of length three pointing to the right from the function <m>y=\abs(x)</m> to the function <m>y=\abs(x-3)</m>.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                              xmin=-8,xmax=8,
                              ymin=-8,ymax=8,
                              xtick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              ytick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              minor xtick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7},
                              minor ytick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7}]
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-4.9:7.9,smooth] {abs(x-3)};
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-7.9:7.9,smooth,color=blue] {abs(x)};
                \addplot[interval,black,thick,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(-5,5) (-2,5)};
                \addplot[interval,black,thick,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(-2,2) (1,2)};
                \addplot[interval,black,thick,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(4,4) (7,4)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure xml:id="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-2">
        <caption><m>\highlight{y=\abs{x}}\,\,\text{and}\,\,\highlightr{y=\abs{x+4}}</m></caption>
        <image>
          <description>
            A graph with several arrows of length four pointing to the left from the function <m>y=\abs(x)</m> to the function <m>y=\abs(x+4)</m>.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                              xmin=-8,xmax=8,
                              ymin=-8,ymax=8,
                              xtick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              ytick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              minor xtick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7},
                              minor ytick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7}]
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-7.9:3.9,smooth] {abs(x+4)};
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-7.9:7.9,smooth,color=blue] {abs(x)};
                \addplot[interval,black,thick,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(6,6) (2,6)};
                \addplot[interval,black,thick,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(1,1) (-3,1)};
                \addplot[interval,black,thick,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(-3,3) (-7,3)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Transformations of type <m>g(x)=f(x) \pm k</m></title>

    <p></p>
    <p>
      Before telling you the graphical effect of adding or subtracting a positive number to <m>f(x)</m>, explore the effect yourself using <xref ref="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-2x">Figure</xref>.  Can you describe the effect using your own words?
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-2x">
      <caption>Add or subtract a positive number to <m>f(x)</m> by dragging the slider.</caption>
      <interactive platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="9:5">
        <slate surface="geogebra" aspect="9:5" source="geogebra/function-vertical-shifts.ggb">
              setPerspective("G");
              setAxisSteps(1, 1, 1, 1);
              setCoordSystem(-8, 8, -8, 8);
              setGridVisible(1);         
              setAxisLabels(1,"x","y","z");
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Assuming that <m>k</m> is a positive number, the graph of <m>y=f(x)+k</m> shifts every point on <m>y=f(x)</m> upward by <m>hk</m> units while the graph of <m>y=f(x)-k</m> shifts every point on <m>y=f(x)</m> downward by <m>k</m> units.
    </p>
    <p>
      The graphs of <m>f(x)=\abs{x}</m> and <m>g(x)=\abs{x}-5</m> are shown in <xref ref="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-3">Figure</xref>.  Notice that <m>g</m> is the result of shifting <m>f</m> downward by 5 units. The graphs of <m>f(x)=\abs{x}</m> and <m>h(x)=\abs{x}+2</m> are shown in <xref ref="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-4">Figure</xref>.  Notice that <m>h</m> is the result of shifting <m>f</m> upward by 2 units.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

      <figure xml:id="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-3">
        <caption><m>\highlight{y=\abs{x}}\,\,\text{and}\,\,\highlightr{y=\abs{x}-5}</m></caption>
        <image>
          <description>
            A graph with several arrows of length five pointing downward from the function <m>y=\abs(x)</m> to the function <m>y=\abs(x)-5</m>.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                              xmin=-8,xmax=8,
                              ymin=-8,ymax=8,
                              xtick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              ytick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              minor xtick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7},
                              minor ytick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7}]
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-7.9:7.9,smooth] {abs(x)-5};
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-7.9:7.9,smooth,color=blue] {abs(x)};
                \addplot[interval,black,thick,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(-7,7) (-7,2)};
                \addplot[interval,black,thick,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(-2,2) (-2,-3)};
                \addplot[interval,black,thick,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(5,5) (5,0)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure xml:id="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-4">
        <caption><m>\highlight{y=\abs{x}}\,\,\text{and}\,\,\highlightr{y=\abs{x}+2}</m></caption>
        <image>
          <description>
            A graph with several arrows of length two pointing upward from the function <m>y=\abs(x)</m> to the function <m>y=\abs(x)+2</m>.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                              xmin=-8,xmax=8,
                              ymin=-8,ymax=8,
                              xtick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              ytick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              minor xtick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7},
                              minor ytick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7}]
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-5.9:5.9,smooth] {abs(x)+2};
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-7.9:7.9,smooth,color=blue] {abs(x)};
                \addplot[interval,thick,black,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(-4,4) (-4,6)};
                \addplot[interval,thick,black,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(1,1) (1,3)};
                \addplot[interval,thick,black,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(5,5) (5,7)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>

    <figure xml:id="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-1">
      <caption>Practice Shift Transformations:  Enter the coordinates for the shifted points A, B, C and then click "Show Transformed Curve" to check your answer.</caption>
      <interactive platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="9:5">
        <slate surface="geogebra" aspect="9:5" source="geogebra/transformation-shift-quiz.ggb">
          setPerspective("G");
          setGridVisible(1);         
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Transformations of type <m>g(x)=f(-x)</m> and <m>g(x)=-f(x)</m></title> 

    <p></p>
    <p>
      Before telling you the graphical effects of having a negative coefficient on <m>x</m> and/or <m>f(x)</m>, explore the effect yourself using <xref ref="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-3x">Figure</xref>.  Can you describe the effect using your own words?
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-3x">
      <caption>Use the buttons to change the sign on <m>x</m> or <m>f(x)</m>.</caption>
      <interactive platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="9:5">
        <slate surface="geogebra" aspect="9:5" source="geogebra/function-reflections.ggb">
              setPerspective("G");
              setAxisSteps(1, 1, 1, 1);
              setCoordSystem(-8, 8, -8, 8);
              setGridVisible(1);         
              setAxisLabels(1,"x","y","z");
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    
    <p>
      The graph of <m>y=f(-x)</m> is a reflection of the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> across the <m>y</m>-axis. The graph of <m>y=-f(x)</m> is a reflection of the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> across the <m>x</m>-axis.
    </p>
    <p>
      The graphs of <m>f(x)=x+5</m> and <m>g(x)=-x+5</m> are shown in <xref ref="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-5">Figure</xref>.  Notice that the two lines are reflections across the <m>y</m>-axis. The graphs of <m>f(x)=x+5</m> and <m>g(x)=-(x+5)</m> are shown in <xref ref="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-6">Figure</xref>.  Notice that the two lines are reflections across the <m>x</m>-axis.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

      <figure xml:id="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-5">
        <caption><m>\highlight{y=x+5}</m> and <m>\highlightr{y=-x+5}</m></caption>
        <image>
          <description>
            A graph of the lines <m>f(x)=x+5</m> and <m>g(x)=-x+5</m>.  Both lines pass through the point <m>(0,5)</m>.  The function <m>f</m> passes through the point <m>(1,6)</m> whereas the function <m>g</m> passes through the point <m>(-1,6)</m>. The function <m>f</m> passes through the point <m>(2,6)</m> whereas the function <m>g</m> passes through the point <m>(-2,6)</m>.  This pattern of common <m>y</m>-coordinates but opposite <m>x</m>-coordinates continues without end in both the positive <m>x</m> direction and the negative <m>x</m> direction.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                              xmin=-8,xmax=8,
                              ymin=-8,ymax=8,
                              xtick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              ytick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              minor xtick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7},
                              minor ytick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7}]
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-2.9:7.9,smooth] {-x+5};
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-7.9:2.9,smooth,color=blue] {x+5};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure xml:id="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-6">
        <caption><m>\highlight{y=x+5}</m> and <m>\highlightr{y=-(x+5)}</m></caption>
        <image>
          <description>
            A graph of the lines <m>f(x)=x+5</m> and <m>g(x)=-(x+5)</m>.  Both lines pass through the point <m>(-5,0)</m>.  The function <m>f</m> passes through the point <m>(-4,1)</m> whereas the function <m>g</m> passes through the point <m>(-4,-1)</m>. The function <m>f</m> passes through the point <m>(-3,2)</m> whereas the function <m>g</m> passes through the point <m>(-3,-2)</m>.  This pattern of common <m>x</m>-coordinates but opposite <m>y</m>-coordinates continues without end in both the positive <m>x</m> direction and the negative <m>x</m> direction.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                              xmin=-8,xmax=8,
                              ymin=-8,ymax=8,
                              xtick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              ytick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                              minor xtick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7},
                              minor ytick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7}]
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-7.9:2.9,smooth] {-x-5};
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-7.9:2.9,smooth,color=blue] {x+5};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Transformations of type <m>g(x)=f(bx)</m> where <m>b \gt 0, b \neq 1</m></title> 

    <p></p>
    <p>
      Before telling you the graphical effect of multiplying <m>x</m> by a positive number other than one, explore the effect yourself using <xref ref="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-4x">Figure</xref>.  Can you describe the effect using your own words?
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-4x">
      <caption>Multiply <m>x</m> by a positive number other than one by dragging the slider.</caption>
      <interactive platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="9:5">
        <slate surface="geogebra" aspect="9:5" source="geogebra/function-horizontal-stretch.ggb">
              setPerspective("G");
              setAxisSteps(1, 1, 1, 1);
              setCoordSystem(-8, 8, -8, 8);
              setGridVisible(1);         
              setAxisLabels(1,"x","y","z");
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    
    <p>
      The graph of <m>y=f(bx), b \gt 0</m> moves the <m>x</m>-coordinate of every point on <m>f</m> by the factor of <m>\frac{1}{b}</m>.  When <m>b \gt 1</m> the result is a horizontal compression.  When <m>0 \lt b \lt 1</m>, the result is a horizontal stretch.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      The graphs of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> and <m>g(x)=(2x)^2</m> are shown in <xref ref="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-7">Figure</xref>.  Notice that every <m>x</m>-coordinate on <m>f</m> has been cut in half on the graph of <m>g</m>.  The result is a horizontal compression of <m>f</m> by a factor of <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.  Three pairs of points have been highlighted to accentuate the effect.  Specifically:
      <md>
        <mrow>(2,4) \rightarrow (1,4)</mrow>
        <mrow>(4,16) \rightarrow (2,16)</mrow>
        <mrow>(-4,16) \rightarrow (-2,16)</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

      <figure xml:id="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-7">
        <caption><m>\highlight{y=x^2}</m> and <m>\highlightr{y=(2x)^2}</m></caption>
        <image>
          <description>
            A graph of the functions <m>y=x^2</m> and <m>y=(2x)^2</m>.  There are three arrows pointing either left or right from the function <m>y=x^2</m> to the function <m>y=(2x)^2</m>.  One arrow originates at the point <m>(-4,16)</m> and terminates at the point <m>(-2,16)</m>.  A second arrow originates at the point <m>(4,16)</m> and terminates at the point <m>(2,16)</m>.  The third arrow originates at the point <m>(2,4)</m> and terminates at the point <m>(1,4)</m>. 
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                              xmin=-10,xmax=10,
                              ymin=-2,ymax=18,
                              xtick={-8,-6,-4,-2,2,4,6,8},
                              ytick={2,4,6,8,10,12,14,16},
                              minor xtick={-9,-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7,9},
                              minor ytick={--1,1,3,5,7,9,11,13,15,17}]
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-2.1:2.1,smooth] {4*x^2};
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-4.2:4.2,smooth,color=blue] {x^2};
                \addplot[interval,thick,black,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(-4,16) (-2,16)};
                \addplot[interval,thick,black,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(4,16) (2,16)};
                \addplot[interval,thick,black,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(2,4) (1,4)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>
     <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      The graphs of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> and <m>g(x)=\left(\frac{1}{3}x\right)^2</m> are shown in <xref ref="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-8">Figure</xref>.  Notice that every <m>x</m>-coordinate on <m>f</m> has been tripled on the graph of <m>g</m>.  The result is a horizontal stretch of <m>f</m> by a factor of <m>3</m>.  Three pairs of points have been highlighted to accentuate the effect.  Specifically:
      <md>
        <mrow>(1,1) \rightarrow (3,1)</mrow>
        <mrow>(2,4) \rightarrow (6,4)</mrow>
        <mrow>(3,9) \rightarrow (9,9)</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

      <figure xml:id="functions-grahical-transformations-figure-8">
        <caption><m>\highlight{y=x^2}</m> and <m>\highlightr{y=\left(\frac{1}{3}x\right)^2}</m></caption>
        <image>
          <description>
            A graph of the functions <m>y=x^2</m> and <m>y=(\frac{1}{3}x)^2</m>.  There are three arrows pointing to the right from the function <m>y=x^2</m> to the function <m>(\frac{1}{3}x)^2</m>.  The bottom arrow start at the point <m>(1,1)</m> and ends at the point <m>(3,1)</m>.  The middle arrow starts at the point <m>(2,4)</m> and ends at the point <m>(6,4)</m>.  The top arrow starts at the point <m>(3,9)</m> and ends at the point <m>(9,9)</m>.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                              xmin=-10,xmax=10,
                              ymin=-2,ymax=18,
                              xtick={-8,-6,-4,-2,2,4,6,8},
                              ytick={2,4,6,8,10,12,14,16},
                              minor xtick={-9,-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7,9},
                              minor ytick={--1,1,3,5,7,9,11,13,15,17}]
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-9.9:9.9,smooth] {(1/9)*x^2};
                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=-4.2:4.2,smooth,color=blue] {x^2};
                \addplot[interval,thick,black,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(1,1) (3,1)};
                \addplot[interval,thick,black,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(3,9) (9,9)};
                \addplot[interval,thick,black,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(2,4) (6,4)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Transformations of type <m>g(x)=a \cdot f(x)</m> where <m>a \gt 0, a \neq 1</m></title> 

    <p></p>
    <p>
      Before telling you the graphical effect of multiplying <m>x</m> by a positive number other than one, explore the effect yourself using <xref ref="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-5x">Figure</xref>.  Can you describe the effect using your own words?
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="functions-graphical-transformations-geogebra-5x">
      <caption>Multiply <m>f(x)</m> by a positive number other than one by dragging the slider.</caption>
      <interactive platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="9:5">
        <slate surface="geogebra" aspect="9:5" source="geogebra/function-vertical-stretch.ggb">
              setPerspective("G");
              setAxisSteps(1, 1, 1, 1);
              setCoordSystem(-8, 8, -8, 8);
              setGridVisible(1);         
              setAxisLabels(1,"x","y","z");
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    
    <p>
      The graph of <m>y=a \cdot f(x), a \gt 0</m> moves the <m>y</m>-coordinate of every point on <m>f</m> by the factor of <m>a</m>.  When <m>a \gt 1</m> the result is a vertical stretch.  When <m>0 \lt a \lt 1</m>, the result is a vertical compression.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

    <p>
